ops.insert: TITLE: I DIDN'T AGREE WITH THE CROWD—THAT'S COOL!
I wanted to share a story about a time when I didn't agree with what most people around me were saying. It was tough, but it taught me a lot.

I work as a financial advisor in a leadership role at a company here in Detroit. As you can see, I am a Black man. I am married to a multicultural woman, and we have two little kids—one is three and the other just turned one. I also stand strong as an LGBTQ ally, so I care a lot about fairness, inclusion, and giving everyone a shot at life.

A few months ago, we had a significant leadership meeting at work. The topic was about improving diversity in our company. Almost everyone agreed that we should start using hiring quotas to bring in more people from underrepresented groups. I could see how much they believed in this idea and understood why, but I didn't fully agree.

In my view, hiring quotas don't fix the root of the problem. They can bring in diverse candidates, sure. But do those people feel included? Do they stay? Do they grow within the company? I think real change comes from creating better mentorship, listening to different voices, and building a culture where everyone feels like they belong.

I tried to explain where I was coming from using real stories from my own team. I talked about how mentorship helped people from all backgrounds feel more confident and respected at work. I also made it clear that I support the goal—more diversity—I just think the how matters a lot.
The conversation didn't shift right away, but a few people came up to me afterward and thanked me for speaking up. They said they hadn't thought about it that way before. That meant a lot.

What I learned is this: It's okay to disagree even when everyone else seems to be on the same page. As long as you stay respectful, honest, and open, your voice can make a difference. It's not always about changing minds right away; sometimes it's just about starting a deeper conversation.

Being different-in how you look, how you think generally about life and yourself or how you choose to live- gives you a unique view. That's not something to hide. Your light is meant to be shared, you never know the number of candles you're lighting up. Your mind and thoughts in general are worth sharing.

You see It is the same feeling I have after sharing the same with you. I wanted to get it off my chest. I wish you knew the much weight i feel lifted over my shoulders. they didn't lie about solving problems is half solving them. Sometimes all it takes to shift the paradigm is just to begin a mind boggling conversation centered on authenticity. Anyway, if you've ever been the one with the unpopular opinion in the room I'd love to hear how you handled it.
